Delta State Government has said it would continue to prioritise job and wealth creation through its twin projects; Skills Training Entrepreneurship Programme (STEP) and Youth Agricultural Entrepreneurs Programme (YAGEP) as critical tools for mitigating youth unemployment and enhancing entrepreneurship development in the state. Governor, Senator Ifeanyi Okowa who disclosed this in Asaba yesterday, the state capital, during an orientation workshop for 2019/2020 STEP Trainers, said over 4,200 previously unemployed Youths in the state had so far been trained, equipped and established to run their enterprises through the STEP and YAGEP platforms from 2015 to 2019. Represented by the Chief Job Creation Officer of the State, Prof Eric Eboh, at the event, the Governor said that the state government had concluded plans to raise the tally with additional 850 beneficiaries in the 2019/2020 circle of the job creation programme. Giving a breakdown of the programme circle within the period under review, the Governor said that in the 2015/2016 circle, 1,329 youths were engaged just as 980 of them were also engaged in the 2016/2017 circle in both STEP and YAGEP. In the 2017/2018, 2018/2019 circles, according to the state Governor, 745 youths and 1,201 youths, respectively were engaged, just as 850 youths have been targeted to benefit  from the twin programmes in the 2019/2020 circle. On the selection process for the 141 trainers currently engaged by the state government, the Governor said that four critical modules which included; Capacity, Functionality, Willingness/Availability as well as Accessibility were deployed. He said that out of the 294 applications received for the position, 213 were accredited, while only 141 of them were successful and engaged having scaled through the outlined module for selection. In his capacity as the Chief Job creation Officer of the State, Prof Eric Eboh, while commending the state Gov­ernor for his sustained efforts in ensuring the success of the programme, enjoined the trainers to rise up to their responsibilities in ensuring that the state government’s efforts were not undermined. He added, “The Office of the Chief Job Creation Officer does not demand or take money of gifts for posting or retention of trainees to training cen­tres. Trainers should desist from giving gifts to staff in any guise whatsoever. Posting was done anonymously based on a predetermined template”